The Higgs-Boson analyzes
The announcement of the probable discovery of the Higgs-Boson has caused some excitement last summer, and for good reason.
In fact, it is believed that this boson is involved in nothing less than the mechanism responsible for the mass of all objects in the universe.
And finally, it is the last particle whose existence is predicted by the standard model - our best or least false - explanation of nature and the behaviour of matter - but has not yet been observed empirically.
But for the physicists it is not yet completely certain that it really is the Higgs.
We know without the shadow of a doubt that we have a real new particle, and that it strongly resembles the Higgs-Boson predicted by the standard model.
In addition, this appears to be confirmed by new data presented this week at a major physics congress in Kyoto, but there is still a lack of data to be completely safe about it.
Nevertheless, let us assume that it is actually Higgs, as there seems to be only a small risk of being deceived, and look at what it is about.
In this world there is a necessarily imperceptible law, which causes two objects to not be present at the same place at the same time.
It is not possible to violate this rule - and try not to be too strong as you will be hurt.
For even if particle physics is a really strange world, it turns out that such a law applies to it as well: the Paulian exclusion principle, which states that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time, if they are in the same state of quantumity, with this state of state consisting of some of their properties in the whole.
The physicists then divide the particles into two categories.
In one corner are the good citizens, who are called Fermione and are kind to the Pauli principle.
And in the other, the bosoons, an evil band of anarchists who are not holy - in any case, not this principle, which means that they can actually be in the same place at the same time.
According to the website The Particle Adventure, these bosons are divided into two groups from the Berkeley laboratories (which, by the way, is absolutely amazing): the mesons that we will not treat here and the \"power particles\" by which the great forces of nature spread and the Higgs boson are somehow related.
But it must be stressed here that these bosons are not all such exotic creatures as one might think.
If you are able to read this chronicle, then only thanks to a boson of exceptional banality: the photon or the light particle, which is the \"bote\" of electromagnetic force.
When a particle accelerates with an electric charge or changes direction, the electromagnetic field is \"tormented\" in exactly that location, like a pebble that was thrown into a pond.
This “storage” creates an electromagnetic wave (light, infrared or ultraviolet radiation, etc.), and this wave is nothing more than a photon and thus one of the boson’s carriers of power.
Stable Field
The same applies to the Higgs-Boson, with the difference that another field, the Higgs field, must be \"tormented\" so that this boson can be shown.
However, the Higgs field is much more stable than the electromagnetic field; the pathogen has to achieve very high energies, a little comparable to a frozen pond whose surface could only be torn by a very large rock.
Therefore, a huge particle accelerator like CERN is required - the Large Hadron Collider is a ring with a size of 27 km! - to achieve such energies.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is again helpful to explain the relationship between the Higgs and the mass.
It is in fact not all particles and not all materials interacting with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do this, but others don't - for example, a sheet of paper would never keep itself in the refrigerator.
And likewise, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those who do have a mass, while the others (such as the photon) do not have a mass.
For what can all these research now \"be good\" asks Mrs. Plamondon?
For science, they are used to review the standard model (SM), and they also enable physicists to accurately examine all differences between the observations and the predictions of the SM.
There are numerous physicists, by the way, who eagerly hope that such deviations will be found, as the slightest difference could open a door to a \"new physics\" and stop some holes of the model.
One must say that the latter still has great shortcomings, since it does not provide an explanation for the gravity (ups!) and the dark matter that forms about 80% of the matter of the universe (renew ups!).
However, such deviations have not been found at CERN until now.
Impacts
The impact of these research on the general population is more difficult to predict, but it would be wrong to assume that there is no evidence.
By the way: in the early 1960s, the pioneers of the laser in the Bell labs did not suspect that their work would trigger such a revolution.
They saw scientific applications, but nothing else.
In fact, the late physicist Willard Boyle - who worked in the Bell Labs where the laser was invented in the 1960s, and who himself developed the first continuous stroke laser (the first ones were pulsed) in 1962 - has already said that the laser was considered to be a “laboratory” at the beginning.
Imagine...
In addition, applications can also come from all the tools that surround research.
For example, Willard Boyle developed a small light sensor during his work in optics in 1969.
Although it was not the original purpose, this sensor now serves all digital cameras worldwide as a \"eye\" and has introduced him to the 2009 Nobel Prize for Physics.
