Poland and Space.
Last week Poland was admitted as a twentieth member of this space authority at a Council of Ministers meeting of the Member States of the European Space Organization ESA. Poland is thus the second member country from the former Eastern bloc (after the Czech Republic, which became a member of ESA on 12 November 2008).
Poland began a close cooperation with ESA in 1994 and participated in several ESA projects in the following years.
The road of Poland into space began much earlier.
Before the Second World War, Polish cosmos enthusiasts were engaged in space travel, so they did not always rely on understanding.
For example, I remember the lecture by A. Šternfeld of 6 December 1933 at the Warsaw Observatory, where the author presented thoughts from his pioneering work, \"Inway to Cosmonautics\".
However, the ideas of the young engineer (born 1905) left the listeners cold, and after years Šternfeld remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadomski had shown interest in his work.
Šternfeld won the Prix REP-Hirsch, which was founded by Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch in 1934.
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) later became an important advocate of astronomy and space.
In Polish magazines he published hundreds of articles and wrote several books on these scientific disciplines.
Gadomski's globally recognized contribution to the development of space has been appreciated, among other things, by the name of one of the craters on the earthward side of the moon.
Already in 1925, a rail-draisine was built in Poland for which a rocket drive was planned.
Unfortunately, the author of the draft and the details of this project remained unknown.
It is not even clear whether the rocket should be used for starting or braking the draisine.
The information for this is exclusively from the contemporary press.
In 1933 the Polish infantry began to deal with rocket-operated bullets.
The research was conducted by the Institut Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia in collaboration with Prof. Mieczyslaw Wolfke and Prof. Gustaw Mokrzyckiegi.
From the documents delivered it is apparent that the research was carried out until the stage of practical testing.
The research was then interrupted by the invasion of the German Wehrmacht.
In 1937, a photoelectric hunting rocket appeared in the press of the design produced by Ing. Rohoziński, and in the following year, the work “Rakieta - torpeda powietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza” by the author Leliwa-Krzywoblocky appeared.
Both projects dealt with the military use of the rocket drive.
Shortly before the war, all projects for military use of rocket technology were coordinated by the temporary Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Committee Doradczo-Naukowy).
The Committee was set up in 1937, but after two years of work his work was completed by the beginning of the war.
Further articles on space appeared after the war thanks to the work of the Polish Space Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne) in the Polish press.
The first mention of this society was made in 1954 in the November issue of the magazine Problemy, in which four extensive articles of space are dedicated.
The article by Prof. M. Subotowicz contains the proposal to establish a space society.
At the time there were already the first projects on satellite technology, and it was anticipated that the exploration of space would have future.
Already in its early days in 1956, the Polish Space Society PTA tried to join the International Space Federation, founded in 1951, and in fact the PTA became an ordinary member in the autumn of 1956.
The following year, the first PTA chairman, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), became Deputy Chairman of the International Federation for Space.
He served until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, the PTA has been involved in the development of the highly successful meteorological rocket (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), the first Polish rocket for scientific research.
The first type, the RM-1, was completed in 1957, the first one was launched on October 10, 1958.
The rocket with a maximum flight height of 1800 m was about 80 cm long and did not weigh very 5 kg.
Later, an improved version, the RM-1A, was built, and in 1959, flight tests began with the RM-2 two-stage rocket in the Błędów desert.
The rocket was 1.4 m long and weighed about 11.5 kg.
Another stage of development should already be able to do real scientific work - the RM-34 rocket should reach a flight height of up to 14.5 km and be used to observe high winds.
In 1962, however, further development was halted.
The first RM rocket was the Meteor-1 rocket developed between 1962 and 1965.
The rocket was designed as a two-stage rocket, its total length was 510 cm and the starting weight was 32,5 kg.
Three types (Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed from this rocket, which differed in the size of the transport space for scientific instruments.
The Meteor-1A rocket has a transport space of 0.4 liters capacity, Meteor-1B of 0.34 litres and Meteor-1C of 0.62 litres.
The maximum flight height was 37 km for all three types.
In 1965 to 1968, the Meteor-2 rocket was developed at the Aviation Institute, whose first flight tests began in October 1970.
Meteor-2 had a starting weight of 380 kg and was capable of transporting a load of 10 kg to a height of about 60 km.
The Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 versions were then built.
It is also worth mentioning that Poland's accession to the COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 followed by the establishment of a national COSPAR committee two years later.
Poland also participated in space research with Soviet satellites in the context of the Intercosmos programme, and in 1978 Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became second intercosmonaut after the Czech Vladimír Remek.
