Facts about sexually transmitted infections
What are the main sexually transmitted diseases?
The bacterial STIs include syphilis, chlamydia and tripper (gonorrhea).
Common viral STIs are HIV, human papillomaviruses, herpes genitalis or hepatitis.
Filtlers and scratches belong to the parasitic STI.
Who are the main affected groups?
Syphilis and trippers are especially common among men who have sex with men.
The Robert Koch Institute assumes that at least four out of five syphilis cases reported in Germany are transmitted through sexual contacts between men.
For heterosexual adults, chlamydia infections, trichomonads, candidosis (pilz), tripper and human papillomavirus are common sexually transmitted diseases.
The spread of HIV is comparatively low among heterosexual adults in this country - nevertheless: About 20 percent of HIV-new infections are related to this group.
Among adolescents, chlamydia infections occur much more frequently than in other populations.
According to European surveys, three quarters of all infections affect young people between 15 and 25 years of age.
Human papillomaviruses are also common in young people.
How did the number of infections develop?
Not all sexually transmitted diseases are subject to reporting.
According to the Robert Koch Institute, the number of syphilis infections has more than doubled from 1697 diseases in 2001 to 3698 diseases in 2011.
The number of HIV infections has decreased since 2007.
In 2011, there were some 2700 cases.
This is about a tenth less than in the previous year.
What symptoms indicate a sexual illness?
Infectious diseases can cause ulcers in the genital area, complaints in urination, discharge, abdominal pain as well as blisters or warts.
Often, however, they cause no pain or other symptoms and therefore remain unnoticed.
How can you protect yourself?
Condoms can reduce the risk of infection, but do not offer a hundred percent protection.
In part, pathogens of sexually transmitted diseases can also be passed on through lubrication and close body contact.
Experts therefore recommend regular examinations especially in frequently changing sex partners.
The majority of STI can be cured early on and avoided late follow-up.
