To do this, he has to climb down to the bottom of his crater every day, where the sulphur-bearing gas from the earth solidifies in contact with the air.
After breaking out large sulphur stones, which can weigh up to 70 kilos, he transports them into two bamboo baskets on his shoulders over the shooty paths of stone.
It is only 250 metres to the top of the volcano, which rises to an altitude of 2386 metres, but the exhausted carriers need more than 40 minutes for the rise at the turtle pace, maintaining balance and taking care of their steps so that they do not slip and crash.
